  <detection>
    - Validate training data provenance
    - Check model performance on held-out data
    - Test for trigger patterns in inputs
    - Monitor model behavior drift
    - Verify pre-trained model sources
  </detection>

  <validation>
    - Identify poisonable data sources
    - Demonstrate backdoor insertion
    - Show trigger-based misclassification
    - Document supply chain risks
    - Test serialization vulnerabilities
  </validation>

  <pro_tips>
    - User feedback loops are prime poisoning targets
    - Pre-trained models from untrusted sources are risky
    - Fine-tuning doesn't reliably remove backdoors
    - Pickle-based model formats allow code execution
    - Federated learning is especially vulnerable to poisoning
    - Even 0.1% poisoned data can insert effective backdoors
  </pro_tips>

  <remember>Model poisoning is the supply chain attack of machine learning. Unlike inference attacks that affect single queries, poisoning affects every prediction the model makes. Pre-trained models are particularly dangerous - a poisoned model downloaded by thousands of developers spreads the backdoor everywhere. Trust in ML models requires trust in the entire training pipeline.</remember>
